{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534369"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:45:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:45:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14923"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14923"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.08,0.71,0.18,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7611"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59386"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7611"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44792"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"1636"},{"type":"tags","id":"4134"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18616"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59386"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Gynaecology clinic for follow-up after a suction curettage two weeks ago. Histopathology has confirmed a partial molar pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is planning to try for another pregnancy soon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. There is no abnormal vaginal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proceed with immediate conception attempts","Attempt conception after one normal BHCG result","Continue BHCG monitoring until negative for three consecutive weeks","Wait twelve months before attempting conception","Recommend permanent contraception"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires appropriate follow-up after evacuation of a partial molar pregnancy. The main priorities are ensuring complete resolution of the molar tissue and preventing confusion from a new pregnancy during the monitoring period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue BHCG monitoring until negative for three consecutive weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is the standard protocol after evacuation of a partial molar pregnancy. This ensures complete resolution and allows early detection of persistent trophoblastic disease, which occurs in about 0.5-1% of partial moles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttempt conception after one normal BHCG result\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate as a single normal result does not confirm complete resolution. Three consecutive normal results are required to ensure the molar tissue has been completely eliminated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed with immediate conception attempts\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as pregnancy would make it impossible to monitor BHCG levels for resolution of the molar pregnancy. Additionally, it would be difficult to distinguish between normal pregnancy BHCG and persistent trophoblastic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommend permanent contraception\u003C/strong\u003E is overly restrictive. The risk of recurrent molar pregnancy is only 1-2%, and most women can safely attempt pregnancy after appropriate follow-up is complete.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWait twelve months before attempting conception\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessarily long. Once BHCG has normalised for three consecutive weeks, there is no medical reason to delay conception unless the patient wishes to do so.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring the monitoring period, reliable contraception should be used. The combined oral contraceptive pill is safe to use. After three consecutive normal BHCG results, conception can be attempted as the risk of recurrence is low. However, early ultrasound in subsequent pregnancies is recommended to confirm normal development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["After evacuation of a partial molar pregnancy, serum beta-human chorionic gonadotropin (BHCG) should be monitored until undetectable for three consecutive weeks.","Reliable contraception should be used until BHCG monitoring is complete to avoid confusion from a new pregnancy.","Most patients can attempt conception after three consecutive normal BHCG results, as the risk of recurrence is low (1-2%)."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Management of gestational trophoblastic disease [Internet]. East Melbourne (AU): RANZCOG; 2020 [cited 2024 Nov 7]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Management-Gestational-Trophoblastic-Disease.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44792"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14923"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44792"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-07T13:27:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-07T13:28:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7611"}},"conten